aerialway.en_description: Used for various forms of transport for passengers and goods that use wires, including cable-cars, chair-lifts and drag-lifts.

drag_lift.en_description: An overhead tow-line for skiers and riders.

platter.en_description: An overhead tow-line for skiers and riders with platters.

t-bar.en_description: An overhead tow-line for skiers and riders with T-shaped carriers for two passengers.

magic_carpet.en_description: A ski lift for small children resembling a conveyor belt.

goods.en_description: A cable supported lift for conveying goods, not passengers.

zip_line.en_description: Zip line, gravity propelled aerial ropeslide like a flying fox or similar

gondola.en_description: An aerialway where the cabins go around in a circle.

mixed_lift.en_description: A mixed lift, containing both gondolas and chairs.

aeroway.en_description: For physical infrastructure used to support aircraft, air travel, spacecraft and space flight.

parking_position.en_description: A location where an airplane can park

runway.en_description: A strip of land on which aircraft can take off and land.

model_runway.en_description: Take-off and landing runway for model aircraft

spaceport.en_description: A spaceport or cosmodrome: a site for launching or receiving spacecraft

airtanker_base.en_description: A location to supply water and retardant to water bombers

control_center.en_description: A facility responsible for controlling aircraft en route in a particular volume of airspace (a Flight Information Region) at high altitudes between airport approaches and departures.

amenity.en_description: For describing useful and important facilities for visitors and residents.

parking_space.en_description: A single parking space on a parking lot.

bench.en_description: A place for people to sit; allows room for several people.

place_of_worship.en_description: A place where religious services are conducted.

school.en_description: A primary or secondary school (pupils typically aged 6 to 18).

bicycle_parking.en_description: A parking space designed for bicycles.

post_office.en_description: A place where letters and parcels may be sent or collected.

parking_entrance.en_description: A entrance to an underground or multi storey parking facility

doctors.en_description: A doctor's office, a place to get medical attention or a check up from a physician.

community_centre.en_description: A place mostly used for local events, festivities and group activities.

charging_station.en_description: A location where an electric vehicle may be charged.

library.en_description: A place to read and/or lend books

marketplace.en_description: A marketplace where goods and services are traded daily or weekly.

college.en_description: A place for further education, a post-secondary education institution which is not a University

university.en_description: An educational institution designed for instruction, examination, or both, of students in many branches of advanced learning.

veterinary.en_description: A place that deals with the prevention, diagnosis and treatment of disease in animals.

courthouse.en_description: A building which is home to a court of law, which administers justice according to the rule of law.

shower.en_description: Public showers, where people can bathe under water sprays

car_rental.en_description: A place from which cars can be rented.

arts_centre.en_description: An arts centre. A venue where a variety of arts are performed or conducted

public_bookcase.en_description: A street furniture containing books. Take one, leave one.

nightclub.en_description: A place to dance and drink at night.

events_venue.en_description: A place that provides facilities for events such as banquets, weddings etc.

lounger.en_description: An object for people to lie down.

research_institute.en_description: A research institute is an establishment endowed for doing research.

training.en_description: Public place where you can get training.

gate.en_description: A section in a wall or fence which can be opened to allow access.

wall.en_description: A freestanding structure, designed to restrict or prevent movement across a boundary, typically made from solid brick, concrete or rocks, and almost always built so that it is opaque to vision.

hedge.en_description: A line of closely spaced shrubs and tree species, which form a barrier or mark the boundary of an area.

kerb.en_description: A stone edging to a pavement or raised path (right side is bottom, left side is top).

retaining_wall.en_description: A structure that holds back soil or rock from a building, structure or area.

block.en_description: One or more large immobile block(s) usually barring free access along a way.

guard_rail.en_description: A rail, typically metal, designed to keep vehicles within their roadway and prevent dangerous collisions

marker.en_description: A physical marker that identifies a boundary

local_authority.en_description: Describes the territory of a local authority

forest_compartment.en_description: A marked subdivision of delimited forest, which is used for planning, management & navigation

political.en_description: Political boundary, such as an electoral ward or parliamentary constituency

national_park.en_description: The boundary of a national park, an area of natural beauty, set aside for conservation and for recreation

place.en_description: The boundaries of a place , when these boundaries can be defined but these are not administrative boundaries

aboriginal_lands.en_description: Boundary of aboriginal/native/indigenous territories and reservations.

maritime.en_description: Maritime boundaries under the UN Convention on the Law of the Sea which are not administrative boundaries: the baseline, contiguous zone, and EEZ.

forest.en_description: A mostly wooded area with explicit boundaries

civil.en_description: A cultural boundary (for example ethnic), different from all official administrative boundaries

hazard.en_description: A designated hazardous area, with a potential source of damage to health, life, property, or any other interest of value

low_emission_zone.en_description: a geographically defined area which seeks to restrict or deter access by certain polluting vehicles with the aim of improving the air quality

statistical.en_description: An official boundary recognised by government for statistical purposes.

disputed.en_description: Tags used on boundaries that are disputed

water_protection_area.en_description: A water protection area to protect surface water and groundwater from contamination.

limited_traffic_zone.en_description: An area that requires authorization for the entry of certain vehicles, sometimes for specific periods.

special_economic_zone.en_description: A government-defined area in which the business and trade laws are different.

administrative_cooperation.en_description: Area where various administrative entities cooperate.

border_zone.en_description: Strip of land near the country border where special restrictions on movement apply

regional_park.en_description: Used for boundaries of different kinds of parks

urban.en_description: It is the urban area of the "city / village" limited by the entrance/exit signs of the zone "traffic_sign=city_limit".

national.en_description: unclear meaning, usage appears to be a mix of various mistakes

exclave.en_description: Part of territory surrounded by alien territory.

treaty.en_description: The boundary of the area of application of a treaty.

building.en_description: To mark the outline of a building, a man-made structure with a roof, standing more or less permanently in one place.

yes.en_description: A building of an unspecified type.

house.en_description: A single dwelling unit usually inhabited by one family.

residential.en_description: A general tag for a building constructed primarily for residential purposes.

detached.en_description: A detached house: a free-standing residential building usually housing a single family.

apartments.en_description: A building arranged into individual dwellings, often on separate floors. May also have retail outlets on the ground floor.

shed.en_description: A small, simple structure used as storage or workshop

industrial.en_description: A building constructed to house some manufacturing process

farm_auxiliary.en_description: A building on a farm that is not a dwelling.

roof.en_description: A building open on at least two sides.

terrace.en_description: The outline of a linear row of residential dwellings, each of which normally has its own entrance, which form a terrace ("row-house" or "townhouse" in North American English).

semidetached_house.en_description: A house that shares a common wall with another on one side.

commercial.en_description: A building constructed for non-specific commercial activities to take place there.

retail.en_description: A building primarily used for selling goods to the general public.

garages.en_description: A block of private garages each with a separate owner.

outbuilding.en_description: A less important building near to and on the same piece of land as a larger building

barn.en_description: An agricultural building that can be used for storage and as a covered workplace.

greenhouse.en_description: A building in which plants are grown

cabin.en_description: A small, roughly built house typically found in rural areas.

service.en_description: Service building usually is a small unmanned building with certain machinery (like pumps or transformers).

static_caravan.en_description: A mobile home (caravan) (semi)permanently left on a single site.

church.en_description: A building that was built as a church.

farm.en_description: A farmhouse is the main building of a farm

warehouse.en_description: A commercial building for storage of goods.

bungalow.en_description: Simple single-storey flat house, bungalow, holiday cottage

ruins.en_description: Frequently used to mark ruined buildings. However, this usage conflicts with general use of building tag. In theory it should only be used for buildings constructed to look like ruins.

allotment_house.en_description: A small outbuilding for short visits in a allotment garden

carport.en_description: A carport is a covered structure used to offer limited protection to vehicles, primarily cars, from the elements.

civic.en_description: A building hosting any civic amenity (town hall, library, swimming pool).

public.en_description: A building constructed as accessible to the general public (town hall, police station, court house).

hospital.en_description: A building which forms part of a hospital.

hotel.en_description: A building designed with separate rooms available for overnight accommodation.

manufacture.en_description: A building constructed to house some manufacturing process, see also tag:building=industrial.

mosque.en_description: A building that was built as a mosque.

ger.en_description: A portable, round tent (yurt or ger)

hangar.en_description: A hangar is a building used for the storage of aeroplanes, helicopters or space-craft.

dormitory.en_description: College or university dormitory for shared living of its students.

college.en_description: A building constructed to house a college.

stable.en_description: A building constructed as a stable for horses

silo.en_description: A silo is a building for storing bulk materials.

transformer_tower.en_description: A small but tall building constructed to comprise a transformer and connect to an overhead power line.

slurry_tank.en_description: A cylindrical concrete structure holding liquid manure.

transportation.en_description: A building related to the public transportation.

sty.en_description: A building for raising domestic pigs.

government.en_description: Building built to house government offices.

temple.en_description: A building that was built as a temple

fire_station.en_description: A building constructed to house fire fighting equipment.

kiosk.en_description: A small one room retail building, with clients not entering the building.

grandstand.en_description: A grandstand at racecourse or sports ground.

houseboat.en_description: A boat (re)constructed as a floating home, staying at a single permanent location.

stilt_house.en_description: Stilt houses are houses raised on piles over the surface of the soil or a body of water.

sports_centre.en_description: A building that was built as a sports centre

trullo.en_description: A stone hut with a conical roof, built without mortar

supermarket.en_description: A building built as a supermarket

pavilion.en_description: A building providing facilities for users of sports grounds

tent.en_description: A building mainly consisting of sheets of fabric or similar

stadium.en_description: A building which was built as stadium.

digester.en_description: A building constructed as a digester, a bioreactor for the production of biogas from biomass.

sports_hall.en_description: A building that was built as a sports hall

container.en_description: A container used as a building.

religious.en_description: A building that was built as a religious building.

bridge.en_description: A building used as a bridge.

wayside_shrine.en_description: A wayside shrine that meets the criteria of a building.

tower.en_description: A tower, that is a building.

conservatory.en_description: Conservatory - a building or room having glass or tarpaulin roofing and walls used as an indoor garden or a sunroom (winter garden).

military.en_description: An unspecific building constructed for military purposes.

beach_hut.en_description: A beach hut: small, usually wooden, and often brightly coloured cabin or shelter above the high tide mark on popular bathing beaches.

shrine.en_description: A building that was built as a shrine

guardhouse.en_description: A small building constructed to house guard(s).

factory.en_description: A building constructed as a factory.

mobile_home.en_description: A mobile home, permanently located at the same location.

presbytery.en_description: A building that was built as a presbytery (where priests live and work).

cathedral.en_description: A building that was built as a cathedral

castle.en_description: A building constructed as a castle.

gatehouse.en_description: An entry control point building, spanning over a highway that enters a city or compound.

riding_hall.en_description: A building that was built as a riding hall or indoor arena

barracks.en_description: A building built to house military personnel or laborers

glasshouse.en_description: A glass building in which plants are grown. Note far more popular building=greenhouse

entrance.en_description: To mark the location of a building entrance.

synagogue.en_description: A building that was built as a synagogue.

livestock.en_description: A building or part of a building that was built for housing livestock

museum.en_description: A building which was designed as a museum.

ship.en_description: A decommissioned ship/submarine which stays in one place.

tech_cab.en_description: Small prefabricated cabin structures for the air-conditioned accommodation of different technology.

convent.en_description: A building constructed as a convent

bell_tower.en_description: Building constructed as a bell tower

windmill.en_description: A building constructed as a traditional windmill, historically used to mill grain with wind power.

brewery.en_description: building constructed as a brewery building

lighthouse.en_description: A lighthouse building - note that it is distinct from marking active light.

kingdom_hall.en_description: A building that was built as a meeting place for Jehovah's Witnesses.

marquee.en_description: A marquee is a tent or easily demountable tent-like building.

palace.en_description: A building constructed as a palace.

porch.en_description: A porch is a covered area adjoining an entrance to a building and usually having a separate roof.

hall_of_residence.en_description: College or university dormitory for shared living of its students.

pagoda.en_description: A building constructed as a pagoda.

quonset_hut.en_description: A lightweight prefabricated structure in the shape of a semicircle.

fire_lookout.en_description: A building originally built for fire spotting.

bath.en_description: A building which was constructed as a bath.

tree_house.en_description: A building constructed around, next to or among the trunk or branches of one or more mature trees while above ground level.

font.en_description: The construction, built as a baptismal font.

ground_station.en_description: A building containing receiving devices to record information from satellites.

fort.en_description: A building constructed as a fort.

swimming_pool.en_description: A building which hosts swimming pool.

roundhouse.en_description: A characteristic semi-circular or circular building constructed to service engines

changing_rooms.en_description: A building designated for changing clothes.

smithy.en_description: Used for a building purpose-built to serve as a smithy or forge.

venta.en_description: Typical Spanish inns generally located in unpopulated and remote rural areas.

data_centre.en_description: A building used to house computers and network equipment.

gurdwara.en_description: A building that was built as a gurdwara

shepherd_shelter.en_description: A building for shepherds in cattle ranges.

friary.en_description: A building constructed as a Franciscan friary

craft.en_description: A place producing or processing customized goods

grinding_mill.en_description: A device that breaks solid materials into smaller pieces by grinding, crushing, or cutting. The aftermath is powdered product, not liquid extract like oil mill.

carpenter.en_description: A workplace or office of carpenters that work with timber to construct, install and maintain buildings, furniture, and other objects.

metal_construction.en_description: Workplace or office of a person who work with metal. This applies to: planning, construction, trade, repair.

winery.en_description: A place where wine is produced

electronics_repair.en_description: Repair shops and service centres which provides repair of computers, phones, appliance etc.

photographer.en_description: A workplace or office of a person who takes photographs using a camera.

electrician.en_description: A person or company that works with electricity or electrical systems.

brewery.en_description: A dedicated building for the making of beer.

tailor.en_description: A place where clothing is made, repaired, or altered professionally, especially suits and men's clothing.

shoemaker.en_description: A place where shoes, boots, sandals, clogs and moccasins are created, repaired or altered to fit personal needs.

plumber.en_description: A workplace or office of a skilled tradesperson who specializes in (drinking) water supply, sewage and drainage systems

sawmill.en_description: A sawmill is a facility where logs are cut into timber

hvac.en_description: A workplace or office of an HVAC system designer (Heating, Ventilating, and Air Conditioning)

caterer.en_description: A workplace or office of one who prepares customized meals for takeout, or provides prepared meals or supplies to a group at social gatherings

window_construction.en_description: A workplace of someone constructing windows

confectionery.en_description: A place where the set of food items that are rich in sugar, any one or type of which is called a confection is produced.

dressmaker.en_description: Dressmaker is a person who makes custom clothing for women, such as dresses, blouses, and evening gowns.

handicraft.en_description: A place where useful and decorative devices are made completely by hand or using only simple tools

gardener.en_description: A workplace or office of a garden designer or a landscape gardener.

stonemason.en_description: A place where rough pieces of rock are shaped into accurate geometrical shapes.

glaziery.en_description: A place where residential, commercial, and artistic glass is selected, cut, installed, replaced, and removed.

painter.en_description: A workplace or office of a house painter which is a tradesman responsible for the painting and decorating of buildings.

joiner.en_description: An artisan who builds things by joining pieces of wood, particularly furniture or ornamental work.

roofer.en_description: A workplace or office of a tradesman who is specialized in roof covering and sealing.

builder.en_description: A workplace or office of a tradesman who performs structural alterations and additions to buildings.

key_cutter.en_description: A place where keys can be duplicated from originals.

upholsterer.en_description: A place where furniture, especially seats are provided with padding, springs, webbing, and fabric or leather covers.

blacksmith.en_description: A place where a blacksmith forges tools, horseshoes, etc. from iron.

pottery.en_description: A place where earthenware, stoneware and porcelain and other ceramic ware is made by potters.

distillery.en_description: An establishment for distilling, especially for distilling alcoholic liquors.

cleaning.en_description: Workplace or office of a person who cleaning building, industrial facilities or windows.

agricultural_engines.en_description: A place where engines and tools for agricultural use are planned and constructed.

jeweller.en_description: A place where necklaces, rings, brooches, earrings and bracelets and other personal adornments are created or repaired.

signmaker.en_description: A maker of signs, mainly for shops and other businesses.

locksmith.en_description: A place where locks and keys are created or repaired.

photographic_laboratory.en_description: A place where photos taken on a film or digital images are transformed into a more permanent form, often on paper or plastic foil.

tiler.en_description: A workplace or office of a person who lays tiles on floors, swimming pools and such.

watchmaker.en_description: A watchmaker is an artisan who makes and repairs watches. Today due to industrial production they mostly repair watches.

clockmaker.en_description: A workplace or office of a clockmaker that is building, repairing or engraving clocks of all sorts.

bakery.en_description: A workplace for fresh bakery goods. No shop.

printer.en_description: A small printing business which produces published works such as newspapers, books, magazines, etc.

welder.en_description: One who unites pieces of metal with high temperature.

floorer.en_description: A workplace or office of a floorer.

tinsmith.en_description: A person who makes and repairs things made of light-coloured metal, particularly tinware.

boatbuilder.en_description: A workplace where boats are planned and constructed

oil_mill.en_description: A mill designed to crush or bruise oil-bearing seeds, such as linseed or peanuts, or other oil-rich vegetable material.

scaffolder.en_description: A workplace or office of a tradesman who builds temporary structure used to support people and material in the construction or repair of buildings and other large structures.

plasterer.en_description: A workplace or office of a tradesman who works with plaster, such as forming a layer of plaster on an interior wall or plaster decorative moldings on ceilings or walls.

optician.en_description: A place where lenses for the correction of a person's vision are designed, fitted and dispensed.

bookbinder.en_description: A workplace for physically assembling a book from a number of sheets of paper.

cabinet_maker.en_description: A person who makes fine wooden furniture

saddler.en_description: A place where saddles or accessories for cars and boats are produced or repaired.

insulation.en_description: A workplace or office of a person who does thermal insulation in buildings.

atelier.en_description: A place where visual artists work

carpet_layer.en_description: A carpet layer is a tradesmen who specializes in laying carpets

dental_technician.en_description: A workplace for dental technician who constructs custom-made restorative and dental appliances

chimney_sweeper.en_description: A workplace or office of a person who cleans chimneys for a living.

sun_protection.en_description: A place where sun protection is made, repaired, or delivered for assembly, especially awnings and shutters.

printmaker.en_description: A producer of fine art prints.

parquet_layer.en_description: A workplace or office of a parquet layer.

cheese.en_description: Dedicated to the making of cheese.

sailmaker.en_description: A workshop of a sailmaker who cleans, repairs and makes sails.

toolmaker.en_description: A workplace of a company that builds complex tools, machine tools, moulds, gauges,... .

goldsmith.en_description: The workplace of a person who forges things out of gold, especially jewelry.

turner.en_description: A workplace or office of a turner.

car_painter.en_description: A place specializing in painting cars.

luthier.en_description: Workshop of a luthier, who makes or repairs stringed wooden musical instruments, such as lutes, violins, and guitars.

engraver.en_description: A workplace or office of an engraver.

pest_control.en_description: A business that offers pest control services

organ_builder.en_description: Organ building is the profession of designing, building, restoring and maintaining pipe organs.

tatami.en_description: A workplace or office of an artisan for tatami mat.

interior_work.en_description: Workplace or office of a person who build non-load-bearing interior walls, especially drywall.

rigger.en_description: The workplace of a person who sets up the rigging for sailboats and sailing ships (or possibly a person who works on ropes, booms, lifts, hoists and the like for a stage production)

door_construction.en_description: A workplace of someone constructing doors

weaver.en_description: Workshop of a person producing something by weaving, may offer products for sale

paver.en_description: The workshop or office of a paver

glassblower.en_description: A person or company that blows bottles or other objects from molten glass.

stand_builder.en_description: A workplace of a company that builds stands/booths for fairs.

water_well_drilling.en_description: A company that drills water wells.

stove_fitter.en_description: A workplace/office of a person / company who designs and builds stoves / tiled stoves.

carpet_cleaner.en_description: A carpet cleaner is a tradesman who specializes in cleaning carpets

piano_tuner.en_description: A piano tuner or technician. A professional that tunes, regulates and makes the maintenance of pianos. Most of them repair simple problems and some restore a whole piano.

photovoltaic.en_description: A workplace or office who installed or planned photovoltaic systems.

information_electronics.en_description: Workplace or office of an information electronics which is a tradesman specialized repairing Television, Radio, monitors, and other electronic components, they build roof aerial, rooftop dish, networks in buildings and more.

cooper.en_description: A person or company that manufacture of containers and vessels mainly made of wood.

candlemaker.en_description: A person who makes candles or a manufactory where candles were made

mint.en_description: A place where coins and medals are hand crafted.

bag_repair.en_description: A place where bags/luggage are repaired.

emergency.en_description: Describes various emergency services, facilities, amenities or the possibility of access for emergency services

fire_hydrant.en_description: An active fire protection measure, and a source of water provided in most urban, suburban, and rural areas with municipal water service to enable fire fighters to tap into the municipal water supply to assist in extinguishing a fire.

access_point.en_description: A sign number which can be used to define your current position in case of an emergency

yes.en_description: Indicates either that a road is accessible to emergency vehicles or that a hospital is equipped to deal with emergencies.

defibrillator.en_description: Defibrillator (AED), an external and portable electronic device that diagnoses and can correct arrhythmia of the heart automatically.

water_tank.en_description: A large water basin or tank for a fire department to take water

siren.en_description: A loud noise maker, such as an air raid siren or a tornado siren.

suction_point.en_description: A preferred point to pump water off a river or other waters for a fire department.

assembly_point.en_description: A designated (safe) place where people can gather or must report to during an emergency or a fire drill

ambulance_station.en_description: A ambulance station is a structure or other area set aside for storage of ambulance vehicles, medical equipment, personal protective equipment, and other medical supplies.

fire_extinguisher.en_description: An active fire protection device used to extinguish or control small fires, often in emergency situations.

life_ring.en_description: A floating ring to throw out to someone who is struggling in water.

fire_water_pond.en_description: A man made or natural pond with water for a fire department.

lifeguard.en_description: A place where a lifeguard is on duty

landing_site.en_description: Preselected flat area for a helicopter to land in an emergency situation

fire_hose.en_description: A high-pressure hose used to carry water or other fire retardant (such as foam) to a fire to extinguish it.

emergency_ward_entrance.en_description: The entrance to an emergency ward.

disaster_help_point.en_description: Marks places using as disaster help points

drinking_water.en_description: A facility that provides drinking water in emergency situations

fire_service_inlet.en_description: A inlet that allows the fire brigade pump water into a building

fire_alarm_box.en_description: A device used for notifying a fire department of a fire.

disaster_response.en_description: A station where equipment and volunteers/paid members are based to work in an area affected by a natural or anthropogenic disaster.

fire_lookout.en_description: A location used for fire spotting.

mountain_rescue.en_description: A mountain rescue base for a team providing search and rescue services in mountainous environments.

first_aid_kit.en_description: A collection of supplies and equipment that is used to give medical treatment

water_rescue.en_description: A water search and rescue station, with rescues carried out by boats or other means.

slipway.en_description: Places that can be used as slipway in an emergency, including places that are not usually used as slipways.

water_rescue_station.en_description: Using of this tag is discouraged, use tag:emergency=water_rescue or tag:emergency=lifeguard instead.

ladder_site.en_description: An installation area for fire engines

key_depot.en_description: Storage of a master key for the fire department.

lifeboat_station.en_description: A lifeboat or Marine Rescue station.

rescue_box.en_description: A box in a mountain or wilderness area, containing a stretcher and first-aid materials

fire_flapper.en_description: A wildland firefighting tool also called a swatter or a beater. It is designed for extinguishing minor fires in rural areas such as heaths.

bleed_control_kit.en_description: A box containing materials to staunch emergency bleeding.

fire_equipment.en_description: A container or trailer with fire fighting equipment in a suburban and forest border area

fire_sand_bin.en_description: A fire sand storage bin designed for the bulk storage of fire sand.

fire_point_stand.en_description: Fire point stand (fire cabinet) presents on the territory of any enterprise and public place. It's often equipped with one or two carbon dioxide type fire extinguishers, pike pole, shovel, bar, fire-arresting sheet, hatchet, and buckets.

standpipe.en_description: A standpipe without a Siamese connection.

throw_bag.en_description: A rope in a bag to throw out to someone who is struggling in water.

rescue_buoy.en_description: A floating buoy to throw out to someone who is struggling in water.

shower.en_description: A shower for use in emergency situations

fire_blanket.en_description: This tag is used to describe fire blankets.

moraine.en_description: Any accumulation of unconsolidated rock debris previously carried by a glacier

outcrop.en_description: A place where the bedrock or superficial deposits previously covered under the soil have become locally exposed

volcanic_vent.en_description: A hole through which the lava erupts.

volcanic_lava_field.en_description: An area with volcanic lava on the ground.

glacial_erratic.en_description: A boulder deposited by a glacier.

meteor_crater.en_description: A crater formed by the impact of a meteor.

volcanic_lava_flow.en_description: The area of a lava flow associated with a specific volcanic eruption.

giants_kettle.en_description: A regular hole in a rock created by the rotation of stones in the bed of a stream.

rock_glacier.en_description: Rock glaciers are mixtures of rock and ice that move slowly downhill when active

hoodoo.en_description: A column of rock with a hat

highway.en_description: Used for roads and road-related facilities.

service.en_description: Generally for access to a building, service station, beach, campsite, industrial estate, business park, etc.

track.en_description: A minor land-access road like a farm or forest track.

footway.en_description: A path mainly or exclusively for pedestrians.

path.en_description: A generic path used by pedestrians, small vehicles, for animal riding or livestock walking. Not used by two-track vehicles. Very broad, non-specific meaning.

crossing.en_description: The location of a street crossing for pedestrians, cyclists, or equestrians

tertiary.en_description: A road linking small settlements, or the local centres of a large town or city.

street_lamp.en_description: A single pole with one or more lights to illuminate the street.

bus_stop.en_description: A bus stop is a place where public buses stop for passengers.

turning_circle.en_description: A widened area of road that allows vehicles to turn more easily.

living_street.en_description: Road with very low speed limits and other pedestrian friendly traffic rules.

traffic_signals.en_description: A traffic signal (or a set of those) for regulating circulation.

trunk.en_description: Important roads that are not motorways.

stop.en_description: A point at which a vehicle must come to a complete stop.

steps.en_description: For flights of steps on footways and paths.

motorway.en_description: High capacity highways designed to safely carry fast motor traffic.

give_way.en_description: Used to mark give way (also known as yield) signs or markings

motorway_link.en_description: The link roads (sliproads / ramps) leading to and from a motorway.

trunk_link.en_description: The link roads (sliproads / ramps) leading to and from a trunk highway

primary_link.en_description: Connecting slip roads/ramps of primary highways

construction.en_description: A highway (road, track or path) currently under construction.

secondary_link.en_description: Connecting slip roads/ramps of secondary highways

tertiary_link.en_description: Connecting slip roads/ramps of tertiary highways

motorway_junction.en_description: An exit from a motorway or other major road.

milestone.en_description: Stone or metal marker on the side of a road indicating the reference and the distance travelled.

platform.en_description: A platform at a bus stop or station.

turning_loop.en_description: A widened area of a highway with a non-traversable island for turning around, often circular and at the end of a road.

proposed.en_description: A road that is about to be built, but where any construction work hasn't yet been started.

bridleway.en_description: A way intended for use by equestrians.

speed_camera.en_description: A fixed road-side or overhead speed camera.

mini_roundabout.en_description: A road junction where the traffic goes around a painted circle or traversable island and has right of way.

emergency_access_point.en_description: Sign number which can be used to define your current position in case of an emergency

passing_place.en_description: A passing place on a single track road.

elevator.en_description: An elevator (or lift) is used to travel vertically, providing passenger and freight access between pathways at different floor levels. May be solely vertical (typical case) or inclined.

raceway.en_description: A racetrack for motorised racing, e.g. cars, motorbikes and karts.

rest_area.en_description: Place where drivers can leave the road to rest, but not refuel.

services.en_description: Place where drivers can leave a road to refuel, rest, or take refreshments.

traffic_mirror.en_description: Mirror that reflects the traffic on one road when direct view is blocked.

busway.en_description: A dedicated roadway for bus rapid transit systems.

emergency_bay.en_description: An area beside a highway where you can safely stop your car in case of breakdown or emergency.

trailhead.en_description: A trailhead is a designated or customary place where a trip on a trail begins or ends.

toll_gantry.en_description: A tag on a node to denote a transponder or camera gantry that exists for the purpose of electronically collecting tolls.

priority.en_description: Identifies an intersection at which one road has the right of way (priority) while another road must stop or give way.

via_ferrata.en_description: A mountain route equipped with fixed cables, stemples, ladders, and bridges where climber is attached to supporting equipment limiting fall.

speed_display.en_description: A dynamic electronic sign that displays the speed of the passer-by motorist

no.en_description: This tag is sometimes used to show that a way is not a (physical) highway on objects where it would not be obvious otherwise.

escape.en_description: Emergency lane beside long descending slopes for trucks to stop after brake failure.

traffic_sign.en_description: The location of an unspecified traffic sign.

bus_guideway.en_description: A busway that is side guided "rails like", not suitable for other traffic.

cyclist_waiting_aid.en_description: Street furniture and devices for cyclists that are intended to make waiting at esp. traffic lights more comfortable.

piste.en_description: Piste segments that do not exists without snow.

historic.en_description: Used for describing various historic features

wayside_cross.en_description: A historical cross along a way, symbol of christian faith.

tomb.en_description: A structure where somebody has been buried.

castle.en_description: Used for various kinds of castles, palaces, fortresses, manors, stately homes, kremlins, shiros and other.

citywalls.en_description: A citywall is a fortification used to defend a city.

manor.en_description: Historic manors/mansions having different use today

church.en_description: A church with a historical value.

milestone.en_description: A historic marker that shows the distance to important destinations

stone.en_description: A stone shaped or placed by man with historical value.

tower.en_description: This property distinguishes a tower as historic

monastery.en_description: Building/place that is a historically significant monastery.

tank.en_description: A decommissioned tank which generally remains in one place

vehicle.en_description: A decommissioned vehicle which generally remains in one place

rune_stone.en_description: Stones, boulders or bedrock with historical runic inscriptions.

ste\u0107ak.en_description: Specifies megalithic gravestone from medieval Bosnia.

high_cross.en_description: An early medieaval standing cross, richly decorated, often with a ring surrounding the crossing point.

mosque.en_description: A mosque with a historical and archaeological value.

mass_path.en_description: Use on relations to combine highways into a mass path.

market_cross.en_description: A cross marking a market place, sometimes moved to a new location.

missile.en_description: An unused and unarmed missile which generally remains in one place.

playground.en_description: A playground: an area designed for children to play.

track.en_description: A track for running, cycling and other non-motorised racing such as horses, greyhounds.

slipway.en_description: A slipway: a ramp for launching a boat into water

oxidation_ditch.en_description: An oxidation ditch of a wastewater treatment plant.

footwear_decontamination.en_description: A facility to decontaminate footwear for hikers.

parish.en_description: Consider using the more used office=religion instead.
